{% call components.section("Style") -%}
  <p>Alerts can be used in the light theme only. There are two alert variants that feature multiple styles, depending on the severity of the message that's being communicated.</p>

  {% call components.example(palette='light') %}
  <div class="centered margin-top--4 margin-bottom--4">
    <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-style-1.svg' | url }}" alt="Anatomy of an alert" style="--example-img-max-width: 591px;">
  </div>
  {%- endcall %}

  <h3>Inline</h3>
  <p>Inline alerts can be placed in a container or a component and shouldn’t block other content. The required elements include a bar or a border, an icon, a title, and a container. Text that provides more information about the alert may or may not be included. Sometimes a close button is required if an inline alert needs to be dismissible.</p>

  {% call components.example(palette='light') %}
  <div class="centered margin-top--4 margin-bottom--4">
    <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-style-2.svg' | url }}" alt="Example of a simple and complex inline alert element" style="--example-img-max-width: 555px;">
  </div>
  {%- endcall %}

  <p>The alternate inline alert style features a border instead of a horizontal line on top which is used to express more urgency or to grab the attention of a user.</p>

  <h3>Toast</h3>
  <p>Toast alerts slide into view in the top right corner of the page and rest on top of content. The required elements include a bar, an icon, a title, a close button, and a white container with a drop shadow. Text that provides more information about the alert may or may not be included.</p>

  {% call components.example(palette='light') %}
  <div class="centered margin-top--4 margin-bottom--4">
    <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-style-3.svg' | url }}" alt="Example of a simple and complex Toast alert element" style="--example-img-max-width: 597px;">
  </div>
  {%- endcall %}

{%- endcall %}


{% call components.section("Usage") -%}
  <p>Alerts are notifications that appear or are generated to communicate with users.</p>

  <h3>Inline</h3>
  <p>Use to present simple information or a local notification, like after a user submits a form with errors. Inline alerts should be informational or identify any actions that are required before a user can continue. They should also have the option to be dismissible.<p>

  <h3>Toast</h3>
  <p>Use to present a notification about an important global event or a change. Toast alerts shouldn’t interrupt a user’s workflow therefore they should always be dismissible.</p>

  <h3>Severity</h3>
  <p>Severity communicates the urgency of an alert. The combination of a status icon, a title, and the container style all help to clarify severity levels of alerts.</p>
