{% call components.section("Best practices") -%}

  <p>Don't use inline alerts to communicate messages about an important global event or a change.</p>
  {% call components.example(palette='wrong') %}
  <div class="centered margin-top--4 margin-bottom--4">
    <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-bestpractice-1.svg' | url }}" alt="Inline alert in the top right corner of a page">
  </div>
  {%- endcall %}

  <p>Don’t use Toast alerts to present simple information or a local notification.</p>
  {% call components.example(palette='wrong') %}
  <div class="centered margin-top--4 margin-bottom--4">
    <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-bestpractice-2.svg' | url }}" alt="Toast alert positioned at the top of a page">
  </div>
  {%- endcall %}


  <p>Don’t use different alert variants in the same area.</p>
  {% call components.example(palette='wrong') %}
  <div class="centered margin-top--4 margin-bottom--4">
    <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-bestpractice-3.svg' | url }}" alt="Inline alert and Toast alert stacked on top of each other">
  </div>
  {%- endcall %}
{%- endcall %}

<hr class="margin-top--10 margin-bottom--10">

{% call components.section("Behavior") -%}
  <h3>Stacking</h3>
  <p>If the same alert variant appears in the same area, they stack. The most recent alert should appear at the top of the stack and push other alerts down. When stacked alerts are dismissed or time out, the remaining alerts will move up and fill the empty space.</p>

  <div class="centered margin-top--4 margin-bottom--4" >
    <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-behavior-1.svg' | url }}" alt="Example of multiple stacked Toast alerts">
  </div>

  <h3>Responsive design</h3>
  <p>On small screens, both alert variants will span the full column and be positioned in the center of the layout. Toast alerts will continue to stack on top of each other, so be mindful of how much vertical space the group will occupy if there are multiple alerts.</p>

{%- endcall %}

